{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T18:32:29.690139+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-20T18:32:30.037681+00:00", "id": 19668769, "conceptrecid": "19668768", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668769", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668768", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19668769", "metadata": {"title": "Restoring Wildlife Access and Airflow to Slaughter Canyon Cave, NM", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668769", "publication_date": "2015", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) In January of 2015, a crew spent six days constructing new cave gates on all four entrances of Slaughter Canyon Cave, a backcountry cave located within Carlsbad Caverns National Park in southeastern New Mexico. The project was conceived by Stan Allison and Shawn Thomas, Cave Technicians in the Cave Resource Office, as a means of replacing the primary cave gate with a bat-friendly cave gate. I In addition, two other entrances to the cave that had been completely sealed off by rock and mortar walls were re-opened. A fourth entrance containing a metal culvert with a metal door that limited wildlife access was replaced with a bat-friendly cave gate. The intent of the project was to restore natural cave microclimate conditions in the entrance area by removing the rock and mortar walls, and to improve wildlife access to all four cave entrances.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Thomas, Shawn", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Allison, Stan", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/32ef20009843ef5b13dafcc9dd7105d0", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/c55fb1595e54988bfcb4f4ecd5f96be380402da7e6c20a1d2814d6a60cbfee9e", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/H39KWWTM", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https